03380nam a22004455i 9780804779708DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222008cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047797087 a10.1515/97808047797082doi  a(DE-B1597)581755  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPOL0010002bisacsh1 aPekkanen, Saadia M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJapan's Aggressive Legalism :bLaw and Foreign Trade Politics Beyond the WTO /cSaadia M. Pekkanen. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b29 tables, 5 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF FIGURES AND TABLES -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tADVISORY BOARD MEMBERS FOR BOOK -- tABBREVIATIONS -- t1 RISE OF LAW IN FOREIGN TRADE POLITICS -- t2 ANTIDUMPING CLASHES WITH THE UNITED STATES -- t3 LEGALITY IN SAFEGUARD DISPUTES WITH CHINA -- t4 THE BURGEONING INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY AGENDA -- t5 INVESTMENT RULES IN PREFERENTIAL TRADE ARRANGEMENTS -- t6 THE EXPANSION OF AGGRESSIVE LEGALISM -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe ways in which law has interacted with concrete interests to reshape Japan's foreign trade politics at the start of the twenty-first century can best be characterized as aggressive legalism. Central to this transformation have been the beneficiaries of this ever more aggressive legalism—Japan's trade-dominant industries with visible stakes in the international economic system. Today, thanks to painstaking and concerted efforts, Japan's aggressive legalism has shifted well beyond its origins in the WTO, and is now not confined to any one multilateral, regional, or bilateral forum. Nor is its thrust limited only to the issues covered in this book, namely, antidumping, safeguards, intellectual property, or investment concerns in FTA diplomacy. Its target is not only the United States, but also rapidly rising new Asian competitors like China; not only foreign governments, but also foreign sectors—even down to specific companies. In the shifting landscape of global and regional realities, aggressive legalism has emerged as the single most cohesive and unquestionably legitimate attempt by Japanese actors to structure favorable outcomes in international trade.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitics -- Asia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Arms Control.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477970840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804779708423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804779708/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles